            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being 21, hidden in the Union Square stockroom, opening a shipment from Italy. He slid a cashmere sport coat from its plastic sheath. The fabric was impossibly soft, a weightless cloud in his hands. He held it to his cheek, breathing in the scent of new wool and quiet luxury. In that moment, the noisy, gritty streets of Richmond felt a million miles away. It wasn't just clothing; it was a confirmation that the world he dreamed of was real, and he was finally touching it.\n\n2.\nThe click of the deadbolt on his Tenderloin apartment door was the loudest sound he\u2019d ever heard. She had just left, her parting shot\u2014\"You'll always just be a shop boy, Robert\"\u2014still hanging in the air. He stood at the window, staring at the streetlights below, the humiliation a hot poker in his gut. He didn't cry. Instead, a cold resolve settled in. That insult became the flint against which he would sharpen his ambition for the next twenty years, a private vow to prove her wrong.\n\n3.\nIt was the mid-90s. A young tech founder, awkward in his hoodie, needed a suit for his first big investor meeting. Robert didn\u2019t just find one; he orchestrated a transformation. He remembers the man\u2019s shoulders straightening as he looked in the three-way mirror, a new confidence settling on him like the fine merino wool. It was then Robert realized his true trade wasn\u2019t selling clothes, but selling poise. He was an architect of self-assurance, a skill no university could teach.\n\n4.\nHis first morning as Store Director, he arrived before sunrise. He unlocked the heavy glass doors himself, the keys feeling solid and permanent in his palm. Inside, the store was a silent, perfectly arranged temple of taste. He walked the floor, adjusting a single silk tie, straighten a cufflink display. He wasn't a boy in the stockroom or a salesman on the floor. He was the conductor. A quiet, profound sense of arrival washed over him. He had finally built the beautiful room he belonged in.\n\n5.\nHis father, retired and stooped, visited him at the boutique once, years ago. Dressed in his Local 38 union jacket, he looked utterly out of place. He watched Robert work, then picked up a bespoke jacket, running a calloused thumb over the hand-sewn buttonhole. \"Good, tight work,\" he'd grunted, looking at Robert with a new kind of respect. \"Like a perfect weld.\" It was the highest praise his father could give, a bridge of craftsmanship built between their two different worlds. Robert felt seen."
